{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563760"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:04:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:04:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16880"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16880"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.03,0.05,0.13,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9570"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110160"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9570"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16880"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92458"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4355"},{"type":"tags","id":"4356"},{"type":"tags","id":"11949"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22591"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41096"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41119"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110160"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the antenatal clinic for her first antenatal visit at ten weeks gestation. She has no significant medical history and takes only folate supplements. A dating scan reveals a dichorionic diamniotic twin pregnancy. She asks whether she can have routine first trimester screening for chromosomal abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate response regarding first trimester screening in this pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Combined first trimester screening can be performed","First trimester screening is not possible in twin pregnancies","Screening should be delayed until the second trimester","Only nuchal translucency measurement should be performed","Diagnostic testing with amniocentesis is the only option"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario addresses the common clinical question of screening options in twin pregnancies. \u003Cstrong\u003ECombined first trimester screening\u003C/strong\u003E (which includes nuchal translucency measurement, maternal serum free \u03b2-human chorionic gonadotropin, and pregnancy-associated plasma protein A) can be performed in dichorionic diamniotic twin pregnancies with good detection rates for chromosomal abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe statement that \u003Cstrong\u003Efirst trimester screening is not possible\u003C/strong\u003E in twin pregnancies is incorrect. While the interpretation may be more complex than in singleton pregnancies, screening can be performed effectively with appropriate adjustments to the risk calculations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUsing \u003Cstrong\u003Eonly nuchal translucency measurement\u003C/strong\u003E without serum markers would reduce the accuracy of screening. The combination of ultrasound and biochemical markers provides the highest detection rates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESuggesting that \u003Cstrong\u003Ediagnostic testing with amniocentesis\u003C/strong\u003E is the only option is incorrect and unnecessarily invasive as a first-line approach. Screening should be offered before considering invasive diagnostic testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelaying screening until the second trimester\u003C/strong\u003E would miss the optimal window for first trimester screening and potentially delay important clinical decision-making.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn dichorionic twin pregnancies, each fetus requires individual risk assessment as they are genetically distinct. The detection rate for trisomy 21 using combined first trimester screening in twin pregnancies is approximately 85-90%, which is comparable to singleton pregnancies. The false positive rate is slightly higher in twin pregnancies (5-7%) compared to singleton pregnancies (3-5%).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Combined first trimester screening can be performed in dichorionic diamniotic twin pregnancies with a detection rate of 85-90% for trisomy 21.","Each fetus in a twin pregnancy requires individual risk assessment for chromosomal abnormalities.","Nuchal translucency measurement combined with maternal serum markers provides the most accurate screening in twin pregnancies."],"references":["Prats P, Rodr\u00edguez I, Comas C, Puerto B. First trimester risk assessment for trisomy 21 in twin pregnancies combining nuchal translucency and first trimester biochemical markers. Prenat Diagn. 2012 Oct;32(10):927-32. doi: 10.1002/pd.3934. Epub 2012 Jul 3. PMID: 22752980.","National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE). Twin and triplet pregnancy [Internet]. London: NICE; 2019 [cited 2024 Dec 4]. Available from: https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng137/resources/twin-and-triplet-pregnancy-pdf-66141724389829."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92458"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16880"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92458"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-28T18:40:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-13T13:31:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"95